One thing I really miss from my 10+ years on the road, was my daily 'runseeing'.

It was my way of getting to know a city, its people, its streets. Sometimes it was all I ever saw  of a city before going back to the hotel, theatre, or ship. 

You take in a lot running through streets of an unknown city. I was always inspired by architecture, the colors, the smells, the textures, the small little shops, the street vendors, the people. 

I ran around the world. Well, 97 countries. And in each one, I took time for myself, to run. To see something new and try to get lost. To take in as much culture I could. 

Looking back on my instagram its literally sweaty, younger, skinnier me posing with something that inspired me from wherever I was in the world. 

Today, I ran the very slippery rain soaked streets of Naples and was reminded how important taking this time is for me, and I vividly remember running these streets before. I even put on an old playlist that consisted of a lot of Jason Mraz. Listen, it was 2011 and I was going through it.

These ‘runs’ mean so much more than the calories burned, or miles run. It’s the adventure of getting lost in a foreign country. The shopfronts that stop me in my tracks. The street art that inspires me. The failed attempts to speak the language to use the bathroom (trust me, I now know the universal body language that works every time). The shrines to fallen football players. The statues that have been ‘tagged’ (sorry about it, Carlo). The people yelling at you in Italian to put pants on because it is freezing. The garbage can I found entertaining. A neon rainbow to remind me how fucking lucky I am. 

I am beyond thankful that Covid grounded me, gave me a home, a family and a community.

But damn, it felt good to run again too.

Take your pick.

I am going to use this Valentine’s Day to announce the incredible honor that is being given to my Husband, Paolo Martini and I by the Ali Forney Center, as this years Luminary Award Honorees. 

When Paolo and I met in Provincetown in 2020 at the height of the pandemic, it was it was his dedication to his work, his gentle and kind spirit, and his sincere and selfless compassion that made me fall in love without hesitation.

Through Paolo’s incredible and groundbreaking work at Moderna and my commitment to The Crown & Anchor we immediately realized not only the responsibility, but the platform we each had to ‘honor, support, celebrate, and elevate’ the LGBTQ+ Community. 

I am so thankful to have found a partner who inspires me each and every day to lead with kindness, generosity, and compassion. 

We are remarkably honored and humbled to be receiving this honor, and hope many of you will consider joining us on May 12th in NYC, donating, or learning more about the incredible work the Ali Forney Center does for our LGBTQ+ Community.

Happy Valentine’s Day, Paolo. 

May we always be fortunate to live our lives filled with such love.

Tonight, we chose Hillary over Beyonce (although, I firmly believe they both ‘run the world’).

Paolo and I were honored to join Secretary Clinton for a very intimate evening, updating us on the work and the future of Hillary Rodham Clinton Leadership Project.

Just over a year ago we were invited by Bryan Rafanelli and Mark Walsh to meet President and Secretary Clinton announcing her new global initiative focusing on democracy, global health and leadership development- especially for women. 

It was just a couple weeks before our wedding, and somehow our plans (or lack there of) became a the topic of conversation over lunch. She was quite distraught to learn we hadn’t chosen our suits or honeymoon destination. 

Tonight, upon greeting us she said, ‘Well you two must still be on your honeymoon’!

We all laughed, as I think that like Hillary, Paolo and I truly believe in the work we are doing. And when you truly believe in your work, stopping (or finding time for a honeymoon) isn’t always an option. 

Each time we get the opportunity to spend time with her, I am in awe of her tenacity and drive, not only to the continued work of The Clinton Foundation, but towards many new endeavors that both necessary and crucial for our future.

She reminded us tonight that for her, slowing down isn’t an option. That she works hard each and every day for her three grandchildren. She works tirelessly to protect their future, our nation’s democracy, and the safety of our planet.

Admittedly I have struggled finding a true work/life balance. We are both so passionate about what we do, we often forget to celebrate each other (or even an occasional date).

Provincetown is a place where many of us have learned to love themselves. 

Where many first find acceptance in all of their Queerness. 

For artists, it's been sancuary where they can experienxe the freedom of true and authentic expression. 

The holidays can leave many people feeling conflicted. The joy that holiday music brings so many, can also represent shame and sorrow for others. 

Its traditions, especially its music and its ‘message’, have not always  included us. 

For the LGBTQ+ community, the magic of holiday music has been diminished by the churches, the choirs, the 'holders of holiday spirit', that have for so long left us out; asking us to come with voices, but to leave behind our hearts and our true selves. 

Provincetown’s Holiday Follies have shown that this music and its ability to inspire is far greater than a ’Silent Night’, or it’s ’Three Kings’. 

This music represents peace. It represents hope. It represents  joy. And if isn’t only for those who Believe. It’s for all of us who choose to 'LOVE one another. His law is LOVE, and His Gospel is PEACE.’ 

This album produced by Yaron Spiwak and Jonathan Hawkins, featuring 15 local Provincetown artists reclaims the true spirt of the holiday, with 13 queerly reimagined seasonal favorites .

Somewhere in the world, we imagine a Queer person hearing this music and for the first time, experiencing its true message of peace, love, and joy. 

After all, loving yourself is the greatest gift of all. And this album is our gift to you.

Almost a month in Florida to 'Spread Queer Cheer', and it kicked my ass.

But, it also reminded me the importance of standing up and speaking out, because that is a privilege. To honor those who came before us and fought, so that our voices could be heard. That supporting one another means LISTENING to one another. Start there.

Celebrate something or someone, each and every day. Life is hard and filled with a lot of noise. Don't make it harder. Celebrate the small victories. Sometimes, even getting out of bed should be met with a bottle of bubbly and a confetti cannon.

Never settle or accept 'whats always been'. It's time to elevate. 

It's time we show up, and make people listen. 

This past month showed me how powerful our voices can be when we use them together. How powerful change can be. And how necessary change is in order for our community to thrive.

When we unite. When we collaborate. When we stand together as one, no one can silence us. 

Together, our voices carry such power. But, they're even more powerful when we take the time to listen. 

Thank you to each of the artists, the venues, the local businesses, the bars, the non profits, the hotels and all of YOU, who made us all feel so loved. Whether we shared a stage, a dressing room, a mini van, a trolley, or a bathhouse hot tub, we felt it.

And to those who held down the fort at home, know that it is because of you, that we were able to share a little bit of Ptown with others, and that is truly a gift. Thank you.
